| Behind the Scenes of Canada's Movie Piracy Law                     |
|   from the backroom-handshakes-and-money-exchanges dept.           |
|   posted by Zonk on Tuesday June 12, @08:43 (Movies)               |
|   http://politics.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/12/1150200     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "Michael Geist's latest Toronto Star column
features a behind-the-scenes look at [0]how Canada got its movie piracy
bill based on internal government documents obtained under the Access to
Information Act. Few will be shocked to learn that Hollywood lobbyists
provided draft legislation months earlier as part of their [1]barrage of
lobbying, though the documents show that advisers to the Minister were
skeptical that the proposal would accomplish anything. From the article:
'The industry's lobby efforts were clearly successful. Ignoring the
inconsistent claims, the absence of evidence that Canadian films are
being affected, the contrary internal advice, and the bracing reality
that Hollywood has acknowledged that the U.S. is by far the largest
source of illegal camcording worldwide notwithstanding its movie piracy
legislation, Bill C-59 is expected to sail through Parliament. In doing
so, Ottawa is sending Canadians two messages. The first is what drew the
industry standing ovation - unauthorized camcording will not be tolerated
in Canada even if it means diverting law enforcement resources from
health and safety issues to movie theatres. The second is that private
meetings, foreign pressures and lobbyist drafted bills is how law gets
made in Canada.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/12/1150200

Links:
    0. http://www.thestar.com/Business/article/223795
    1. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K3IpXAbi5Dw


